ON A HOT SUMMER AFTERNOON FREIGHT TRAIN 230-01 WITH UNITS 757-756-2036-4601-2045 AND 77 LOADS, 4 EMPTIES, 9660 TONS WAS HEADING EASTBOUND AT10 MPH AT MP 82.7 NEAR CHARLES CITY, IA WHEN FIVE COVERED HOPPERS LOADED WITH CORN DERAILED. THE ENGINEER STATED THAT HE FELT A JERK IN THETRAIN AND THE AIR WENT INTO EMERGENCY. AFTER STOPPING, THE CREW INSPECTED THE TRAIN AND FOUND THE 65TH THROUGH 69TH CARSFROM THE HEAD END ALL LAYING ON THEIR SIDES. SOO 84776 WAS LAYING ON IT'S SIDE TO THE NORTH, WHILE S00 88380, 74035, MILW 378, AND MILW 1286 WERE LAYING TO THE SOUTH. IN ADDITION, GNWR 301315 WHICH WAS NOT DERAILED, DID NOT SUN A BENT CORNER POST. THE MAIN LINE WAS BLOCKED AND SUSTAINED SEVERE DAMAGE FOR ABOUT 360 FEET. THE POINT OF DERAILMENT WAS UNDER A 10 MPH RESTRICTION BY TRACK BULLETIN AND HAS BEEN WORKED BY TIE GANG WORKING IN THAT AREA. THE TIE GANG WAS WORKING BETWEEN MP 82.0 AND MP 83.8, AND THE DERAILMENT OCCURRED AT MP 82.7. CAUSE OF DERAILMENT WAS DETERMINED TO HAVE BEEN MISSING ANCHORS AND SOME TIES NOT SPIKED. THIS COUPLED WITH 86 DEGREES & HEAVILY LOADED TRAIN, CAUSED TRACK TO BUCKLE.NoneNoneNone
